"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[4099],{4099:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Cloud Layer spec mandates: \'No public IP on database\' and \'Private subnets for databases.\' Why must production databases live in private subnets, never public subnets?","options":["AWS charges lower data transfer fees for traffic that stays within private subnets","Private subnets eliminate internet routing to the database — only resources inside the VPC (your API servers) can reach port 5432, removing an entire class of external attack surface that would exist if the database had a public IP","RDS instances in public subnets cannot use SSL/TLS connections","Public subnet databases cannot be included in Multi-AZ failover configurations"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec\'s VPC design: public subnets contain load balancers and NAT Gateways; private subnets contain API servers and databases. A database with a public IP is directly reachable from the internet — every password brute-force attack, every PostgreSQL CVE exploit, every misconfigured firewall becomes a direct threat. In a private subnet, the attacker must first compromise something inside the VPC before they can reach the database port. The checklist: \'Private subnets for databases\' and \'Security groups with least-privilege.\'","hint":"If a database has a public IP, what can an attacker on the internet attempt directly? What does \'private subnet\' prevent?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Cloud networking diagram shows public subnets (load balancers, NAT Gateway) and private subnets (API servers, databases) within the same VPC. Why use a NAT Gateway for private subnets instead of giving them direct internet access?","options":["NAT Gateways improve download bandwidth for private subnet resources by using AWS\'s backbone network","Private subnets with direct internet access cost more per hour than NAT Gateway routing","NAT Gateway lets private resources initiate outbound requests (npm install, AWS API calls) without accepting ANY inbound internet traffic — the private resource has no public IP and is unreachable from outside the VPC","NAT Gateway is required by AWS for VPC peering connections between different regions"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec\'s VPC CIDR is `10.0.0.0/16` with public subnets `10.0.1.0/24` for internet-facing resources and private subnets for backend services. NAT Gateway provides one-directional internet access: private resources can SEND requests out (to fetch dependencies, call AWS APIs), but nothing can INITIATE a connection IN. This is fundamentally different from a public IP, which allows bidirectional connections. The spec requires \'VPC Flow Logs enabled\' to monitor this traffic.","hint":"Think about the direction of connections — NAT allows outbound-only. What happens if someone tries to connect inbound to a private subnet resource?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"What critical Kubernetes configuration is missing from this production Deployment?","code":"apiVersion: apps/v1\\nkind: Deployment\\nspec:\\n  replicas: 3\\n  template:\\n    spec:\\n      containers:\\n      - name: api\\n        image: myapp:a3f29bc1\\n        ports:\\n        - containerPort: 3000\\n        resources:\\n          limits:\\n            memory: \\"512Mi\\"\\n            cpu: \\"1000m\\"","codeLanguage":"yaml","options":["The `replicas` field should be at least 5 for high availability in production","Resource `requests` are missing — without them Kubernetes cannot make intelligent scheduling decisions: pods may be placed on overloaded nodes, causing OOMKill events when the node\'s actual memory is exhausted despite the limit appearing available","The `image` tag should use a full SHA256 digest instead of a git SHA abbreviation","The `memory` limit should be specified in gigabytes (`1Gi`) not mebibytes for production workloads"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec shows: `resources.requests.memory: \'256Mi\'` and `resources.requests.cpu: \'250m\'` alongside limits. `requests` are the guaranteed allocation — Kubernetes uses them for scheduling decisions (placing pods on nodes with sufficient capacity). `limits` are the ceiling. Without requests, Kubernetes schedules pods on any node, potentially overcommitting. When the node runs out of memory, the kernel OOM-kills containers with the highest memory usage — often your production API. The spec requires both requests and limits.","hint":"Kubernetes uses `requests` for scheduling and `limits` as a ceiling. What can\'t Kubernetes do without knowing the resource requirements (requests)?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"You have 3 pods across 3 Availability Zones. AZ-C fails — Kubernetes reschedules the lost pod. All 3 pods land on AZ-A. Shortly after, AZ-A degrades under the increased load. What prevents this scenario?","options":["Nothing — Kubernetes automatically rebalances pods across AZs within 10 minutes using the descheduler","Kubernetes won\'t schedule all pods on one AZ because the default affinity rules prevent it","Add `topologySpreadConstraints` with `maxSkew: 1` and `topologyKey: topology.kubernetes.io/zone` — this enforces that pods are distributed as evenly as possible across AZs, preventing concentration on a single zone after failover","The load balancer will route traffic away from AZ-A automatically, so pod placement doesn\'t matter"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents min 3 replicas, one per AZ. By default, Kubernetes schedules based on resource availability — after AZ-C fails, AZ-A and AZ-B both have capacity, but without spread constraints, all 3 pods may land on AZ-A. `topologySpreadConstraints` with `maxSkew: 1` ensures pods are distributed across the `zone` topology key — Kubernetes won\'t place more than 1 extra pod on any zone compared to others. The spec also recommends pod anti-affinity rules as an additional safeguard.","hint":"After a zone failure, Kubernetes reschedules freely based on available capacity. What K8s feature ENFORCES minimum distribution across zones?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Cloud Production Checklist, what is the minimum Availability Zone (AZ) deployment requirement and what specific risk does a single-AZ deployment fail to protect against?","options":["1 AZ is acceptable when using managed services like RDS Multi-AZ — the service handles its own redundancy","Minimum 2 AZs for stateless services; 3 AZs for stateful services — single-AZ deployment fails to protect against an AZ-level failure (hardware fault, power outage, cooling failure) which AWS history shows occurs multiple times per year per region","4 AZs are required for PCI-DSS compliance in financial applications","Single-region AZs don\'t provide sufficient isolation — only multi-region deployment meets production standards"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec lists \'Single AZ deployment\' as a Common Mistake and requires \'Multi-AZ deployment (minimum 2 AZs).\' AZ-level failures happen — AWS has documented AZ outages in us-east-1, eu-west-1, and ap-southeast-1. Each AZ is a separate data center with independent power, cooling, and networking. A single-AZ deployment goes entirely offline during an AZ failure. Two AZs means 50% capacity survives; three AZs means ~67% capacity survives — sufficient to handle the load while AWS recovers the failed AZ.","hint":"An AZ is a separate physical data center — what happens to your application if that data center loses power or networking for 30 minutes?"}]')}}]);